Learning Objectives

Learningobjectives

  • Namethemajorcentresandstructures of the CNS involved in the motorpathways and describe theirroles in broad terms.
  • Understand the use of deep brain stimulation of thebasalgangliain thetreatment movementdisorderssuchasParkinsonsdisease.

Motor Control

The intention to contract a muscle begins inmotor association(premotor) area of frontal lobes

    • Where we plan our behavior

Program transmitted to neurons of theprecentral gyrus(primarymotor area)

  • Where neurons compile aprogram for degree and sequence ofmuscle contractionrequired for an action
    • These neurons send signals to the brainstem and spinal cordleading ultimately to muscle contractions

Motor Control2

Precentralgyrusalso exhibitssomatotopy

    • Neurons fortoemovement are deep in the longitudinal fissure ofthe medial side of thegyrus
    • The summit of thegyruscontrols thetrunk, shoulder, andarm
    • Theinferolateralregion controls thefacial muscles
    • Motor homunculus has adistortedlook because the amount ofcortex devoted to a given body region is proportional to thenumber of muscles and motor units in that body region (notbody region size)

Motor Control

Pyramidal cellsof theprecentralgyrusare calledupper motor neurons

    • Their fibers project caudally
    • About 19 million fibers ending in nuclei of the brainstem
    • About 1 million forming the corticospinal tracts

Lateral corticospinaltracts on each side of the spinal cord

    • Most fibers form this track
    • Decussate in lower medulla oblongata
    • In brainstem or spinal cord, the fibers from upper motor neuronssynapse withlower motor neuronswhose axons innervate skeletalmuscles

Motor Control

Anterior (ventral) corticospinal tractthat descends in theipsilateral side of spinal cord

  • Only minority of fibers
  • decussates inferiorly(like lateral tract, they ultimately controlcontralateral muscles)
  • control of muscles in the trunk

Basal nucleiandcerebellumare also important in muscle control

Motor Control5

Cerebellum

    • Highly important inmotor coordination
    • Aids inlearningmotor skills
    • Maintains muscletoneandposture
    • Smoothsmuscle contraction
    • Coordinates eye and body movements
    • Coordinates motions of different joints with each other
    • Lesions can cause ataxiaclumsy, awkward gait

Motor Control4

Basal nuclei

    • Important motor functions include helping to control:
      • Onsetandcessationof intentional movements
    • Lie in afeedback circuitfrom the cerebrum, to the basal nuclei,to the thalamus, and back to the cerebrum
    • Dyskinesiasmovement disorders caused by lesions in the basalnuclei involving abnormal movement initiation

The Basal Nuclei

Basal nucleimasses of cerebral gray matter buried deep in thewhite matter, lateral to the thalamus

The basal ganglia comprise four principal structures:the striatum,globuspallidus,substantianigra, andsubthalamicnucleus.

Striatum

  • separated by the internal capsule into thecaudate nucleusandtheputamen
  • major input structurereceiving prominent projections from thecerebral cortex, brain stem, and thalamus.

The Basal Nuclei

Globus pallidus2 nuclei:

  • Internal segmentmajor output structure of basal ganglia.
  • External segment-intrinsic circuitry.

Substantianigra2 nuclei:

  • Parsreticulata-output structure of basal ganglia.
  • Pars compacta-contains dopaminergic cells that projectheavily to the striatum and other nuclei of the basal ganglia.Regulates reward pathway.

Subthalamicnuclei-excitatory input from cortex and thalamus,inhibitory input fromGPe. Excitatory output toGPi.

Output:GPiandSNrkeep downstream centers undertonic inhibitory control,(e.g. preventing the occurrence of involuntary movements).

  • Descending pathway to brainstem and spinal cord
  • Ascending pathway to cortex via thalamus (feedback loop)

Most projections in the striatum are inhibitory (GABAergic)

Input: From cortex to striatum. Modifies this widespread tonic inhibition duringvoluntary action in a specific way to support the desired goals.

Continuously samples inputs from cortices. Provide information about currentgoals, context, alternative actions, and related costs.

Dopamine modulation: Cortex-tobasal ganglia information flow is stronglymodulated by dopamine transients fromSNc. Important for reinforcementlearning and facilitate the initiation and modulate the vigor of self-pacedmovements.

The basal gangliathalamocortical circuitry

Motor circuit: cortical input tostriatum

Cortex provides a specific movement plan

Basal ganglia evaluate it against additional contextual information and tocommit to executing it.

  • > drive descending motorcentresin brainstem and spinal cord.
  • > provide feedback to cortex on what motor plans have been executed.

Selection and initiation of actions

Direct pathway: cortex-> striatum->GPiandSNr

Indirect pathway: cortex-> striatum->GPeor STN->GPiandSNr

Hyperdirectpathwaycortex-> STN->GPiandSNr

Dopamine pathway: released bySNc. Different effect on two pathways

    • Direct pathway: D1-receptormore excitable
    • Indirect pathway: D2-receptorless excitable

Motor circuit: intrinsic circuitry

Hypothesis:

  • direct pathway-> inhibiting specific neurons to release the desired movement
  • indirect pathway-> disinhibiting other neurons to suppress specific competingmovements.
  • hyperdirectpathway-> suppress other general movements.
  • dopamine pathway-> drive activation of learning movement that results in reward

The basal gangliathalamocortical circuitry

Dopamine input fromSNctostriatum

SNcprovides dopamine input to striatum

  • Lack of dopamine input is a pathological hallmark of Parkinsons disease
    • Leads to impairment in self-paced movement initiation and slowness ofmovement
  • Dopamine pathway implicated in
    • Motivating and initiating movement
    • Invigorating movement
    • Learning rewarding behavior/movements and suppressing aversivebehavior/movements
